    "_feedback": {
      "title": "",
      "correct": "<p><strong>That's right!</strong></p><p>There is no lack of data, in fact it is the opposite “too much data” that often leads to a greater ethical challenge. Having too much data makes it hard to manage and apply good data management principles such as quality control. A dataset can be evaluated a s high quality, but often quality does not consider bias. One of the biggest challenges arises from bias in data collection. Understanding the purpose for data collection, any targets and also the goals (or even geographic location) of the organisation that collected, stewarded the data, &nbsp;will help understand if the data could be biased.&nbsp;</p><p>Even the most respected research areas such as medical, have been discovered as having historical biases that mean most medical procedures are biassed toward the male anatomy.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>",
      "_incorrect": {
        "final": "<p><strong>Are you sure about that?</strong></p><p>There is no lack of data, in fact it is the opposite “too much data” that often leads to a greater ethical challenge. Having too much data makes it hard to manage and apply good data management principles such as quality control. A dataset can be evaluated a s high quality, but often quality does not consider bias. One of the biggest challenges arises from bias in data collection. Understanding the purpose for data collection, any targets and also the goals (or even geographic location) of the organisation that collected, stewarded the data, &nbsp;will help understand if the data could be biased.&nbsp;</p><p>Even the most respected research areas such as medical, have been discovered as having historical biases that mean most medical procedures are biassed toward the male anatomy.&nbsp;</p>",
